After the Free International Order
The Cambridge—Many analysts believe that the free international order ended with China's rise and the election of U.S. President Donald Trump.
But if Joe Biden defeated Trump in the November election, should he try to revive it?
The result may not be that way, but he must find some alternative choice.
Critics point out that the U.S. order after 1945 was neither global nor always very free, which is correct.
It will exclude more than half of the world (including the Soviet bloc and China) and include many authoritarian countries.
US hegemony is always exaggerated.
Despite this, the most powerful nations must take the lead in creating global public goods, otherwise they cannot be provided — and Americans will suffer as a result.
The current pandemic is a good example.
The real goal of the Biden government should be to establish a system of international institutions based on rules, with different members participating in handling different affairs.
Will China and Russia be willing to participate?
In the 1990s and 21st century, neither country could balance the power of the US, while the US dominated and clung to the pursuit of free value principles above sovereignty.
The US bombed Serbia and invaded Iraq without UN Security Council approval.
It also supported a "Responsibility to Protect" resolution adopted by the UN General Assembly in 2005, aimed at providing protection to citizens who were cruelly treated by their own government – the US later used this principle in 2011 to justify bombing Libya to protect civilians in Benghazi.
Critics have described this record as American hubris in the post-Cold War period — for example, when the NATO-led intervention in Libya ultimately led to regime change, Russia and China felt deceived — while defenders of this action have described it as the natural evolution of international humanitarian law.
Regardless of how, the growth of Chinese and Russian power has more strictly limited free interventionism.
So what's left?
Russia and China emphasize the sovereignty principles stipulated in the United Nations Charter, which stipulate that countries can only wage war in self-defense or after receiving approval from the Security Council.
Since 1945, instances of occupying a neighboring country's territory by force have been extremely rare, and once they occur, they will bear a heavy price due to sanctions (like Russia's annexation of Crimea in 2014).
Furthermore, the Security Council frequently authorizes the deployment of peacekeeping forces in countries in distress, and political cooperation has also successfully limited the proliferation of mass destruction weapons and intercontinental ballistic missiles.
This order dimension, which is based on rules, is still crucial.
Specifically, in terms of economic relationships, the world needs to revise the rules.
Even before the pandemic, China's cross-bred state capitalism had supported the unfair mercantilist model, which distorted the functions of the World Trade Organization.
This would lead to a decoupling of the global supply chain, especially when national security is at risk.
Although China complains that the US is blocking companies like Huawei from building 5G communication networks in the West, the US stance is consistent with sovereignty requirements.
Ultimately, China blocked the operation of Google, Facebook, and Twitter in China due to security reasons.
Negotiations for new trade rules would help prevent the escalation of decoupling.
At the same time, despite the current crisis, cooperation in key financial sectors remains very robust.
On the other hand, mutual dependence in the ecological field has created insurmountable barriers in the face of sovereignty, because the threats are transnational.
No matter how economic globalization is hampered, environmental globalization will continue because it is subject to biological and physical laws, and contemporary geopolitics has no effect on it.
The issues mentioned above threaten everyone, but no country has the ability to solve the problem independently.
Even in issues like the 2019 new crown epidemic and climate change, power also has a so-called positive and maintenance dimension.
Under such a premise, simply thinking about exercising power over others is not enough.
We must also think from the dimension of exercising power together with other countries.
The Paris Climate Agreement and the World Health Organization have helped us and others.
Since Nixon and Mao met in 1972, despite the ideological differences, it did not affect the cooperation between China and the US.
Biden's problem is whether the two countries can cooperate to produce global public goods while engaging in competition in the traditional great power competition field.
The issue of network space is a new and important one — — because it has a certain transnational nature, but it is also controlled by sovereign governments.
The Internet has been partially fragmented.
Rules on internet freedom and privacy can be established within democratic countries, but these rules will not be recognized by authoritarian countries.
Just as the Global Cybersecurity Commission suggested, if authoritarian regimes also want to achieve connectivity, then some rules that prohibit tampering with the basic structure of the internet are also in their interests.
However, when they use proxy forces to launch information warfare or intervene in elections (such practices infringe on sovereignty), they must strengthen regulations such as the restrictions on escalating maritime incidents negotiated by the United States and the Soviet Union during the Cold War (although ideological hostility still exists).
The United States and like-minded countries must openly declare the regulations they intend to uphold and establish the necessary deterrents.
Maintaining the free values of the cyber space does not mean that the United States unilaterally disarms.
On the contrary, the United States should differentiate between publicly allowed soft power and secret information warfare and hard power, and must definitely retaliate when the other side launches secret information warfare.
It is allowed to allow Russia and China to publicly broadcast programs and broadcasts, but manipulating social media and unified secret actions are not allowed.
Moreover, the US will continue to criticize the human rights records of these countries.
A public opinion survey showed that the American public wants to avoid military intervention, but does not want to withdraw from the alliance or multilateral cooperation.
And the public still values their values.
If Biden is elected, the problems he faces are not whether to restore the free international order.
The issue at hand is whether the United States can collaborate with core ally countries to promote democracy and human rights, and at the same time cooperate with a wider range of countries to manage the need for a rule-based international system to address transnational threats such as climate change, pandemics, cyber attacks, terrorism, and economic turmoil.
